Fluorescence quenching is the decrease in the quantum yield of fluorescence from a fluorophore induced by a variety of molecular interactions, such as excited-state reactions, energy transfer, ground-state complex formation, and collisional quenching [23]. The different mechanisms of quenching are usually classified as either dynamic quenching or static quenching, which can be distinguished based on different dependencies on temperature and viscosity or preferably by lifetime measurements. Given that a higher temperature resulted in higher diffusion coefficients, the dynamic quenching constants will increase with increasing temperature. By contrast, the increase in temperature is likely to result in decreased stability of complexes. Thus, the values of the static quenching constants are expected to be smaller [22, 28]. The well-known Stern–Volmer equation was used to confirm the mechanism [29], as follows:6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
